1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,170
Paul, I'm pleased to say, got the point.

2
00:00:03,361 --> 00:00:06,770
He learned the practical value of doing what's right.

3
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:11,091
I then proposed he sit down and retake the examination.

4
00:00:11,361 --> 00:00:15,091
In answer to his question, but what about my dismissal?

5
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:19,491
I said, I know what the regulations say about cheating.

6
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:24,371
But you know, if we dismissed all students who have cheated in any way,

7
00:00:24,480 --> 00:00:26,770
half the professors would have to leave.

8
00:00:26,960 --> 00:00:32,850
And if we dismissed all students who thought about cheating, the university would have to shut down.

9
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:37,330
So I'm forgetting this whole incident if you'll do me a favor.

10
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:39,330
Gladly, he said.

11
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:46,611
I walked over to my bookshelf, took down my personal copy of Fifty Years with the Golden Rule,

12
00:00:46,640 --> 00:00:50,690
and said, Paul, read this book and return it.

13
00:00:50,881 --> 00:00:58,531
See how, in J.C. Penney's own words, just doing what's right made him one of America's richest men.

14
00:00:59,280 --> 00:01:04,690
Doing what's right keeps your conscience satisfied, and this builds self-confidence.

15
00:01:04,960 --> 00:01:09,730
When we do what is known to be wrong, two negative things happen.

16
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:14,131
First, we feel guilt and this guilt eats away confidence.

17
00:01:14,321 --> 00:01:19,651
Second, other people sooner or later find out and lose confidence in us.

18
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:22,931
Do what's right and keep your confidence.

19
00:01:23,200 --> 00:01:26,131
That's thinking yourself to success.

